 explore why, how and by whom these acts have been committed through recent history.Interdisciplinary in scope, Destruction and human remains will appeal to readers interested in the history and implications of genocide and mass violence, including researchers in anthropology, sociology, history, politics and modern warfare.The research program leading to this publication has received funding from the European Research Council under the European Union's Seventh Framework Programme (FP/2007-2013) / ERC Grant Agreement n° 283-617.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGenocide. 0aHomicidexHistory. 0aInternational law. 0aMass burials. 0aMass murder. 0aMass shootings. 0aWar crimes. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aArgentina.  aArmenia.  aExtermination.  aGenocide.  aHolocaust.  aRwanda.  aconcealment.  adisposal.  aexhumation.  ahuman remains.  amass violence.  anecropolitics.1 a van Pelt, Robert Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnstett, Élisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnstett, Élisabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBergholz, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDreyfus, Jean-Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDreyfus, Jean-Marc, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKorman, Rémi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKévorkian, Raymond H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMailänder, Elissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMakaremi, C